  "prompt": "How do astronomers calculate the orbital speed of a celestial body?",
  "response": "Astronomers calculate the orbital speed of a celestial body using several key methods and principles:\n\n1. Kepler's Laws of Planetary Motion\n- Use the orbital period and semi-major axis of the orbit\n- Apply the formula: v = \u221a(GM/r)\n- Where G is gravitational constant, M is mass of central body, r is orbital radius\n\n2. Orbital Velocity Equation\n- v = 2\u03c0r/T\n- Where v is velocity, r is orbital radius, T is orbital period\n\n3. Gravitational Mechanics\n- Utilize Newton's law of universal gravitation\n- Calculate gravitational force between objects\n- Determine balance between gravitational pull and centripetal motion\n\n4. Observational Techniques\n- Track position changes over time\n- Use telescopes and precise measurement instruments\n- Employ Doppler spectroscopy to measure radial velocity\n\n5. Mathematical Models\n- Use computer simulations\n- Incorporate complex gravitational interactions\n- Account for multiple body interactions\n\n6. Specific Instruments\n- Precise tracking telescopes\n- Satellite-based observation systems\n- Spectroscopic instruments\n\nThese methods allow astronomers to calculate orbital speeds with high precision across various celestial scales, from planetary to galactic systems.",
